      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>Amino acids can be prepared by reaction of alkyl halides with diethyl acetamidomalonate, followed by heating the initial alkylation product with aqueous HCl. Show how you would prepare alanine, CH<sub>3</sub>CH(NH<sub>2</sub>)CO<sub>2</sub>H, one of the twenty amino acids found in proteins, and propose a mechanism for acid-catalyzed conversion of the initial alkylation product to the amino acid.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBaGtZIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--0a2cc8e0d8a1dbc2a37171653a040cfd3e03a4af/OChem_22_EC_027.jpg\" alt=\"The structure of diethyl acetamidomalonate where diethyl malonate is substituted with an acetamide group.\">\n",
